instrument.description: The oggez is a mid-size hand-held wooden musical instrument.  The musician uses a leather bellows to send air over interior reeds.  The desired pitch is selected using a wooden keyboard.  The instrument has a four octave range going from a mid-low to a very high pitch.  At all pitches, the instrument has a wobbling quavering timbre.  It has three registers.  The low register has a reedy rugged muddy timbre.  The middle register begins at mid-high pitch and has a thin muddy timbre.  The high register begins at high pitch and has a rippling timbre.

The kadän is a small hand-held stone musical instrument.  The musician uses a leather bellows to send air over interior reeds.  The desired pitch is selected using a ceramic keyboard.  The instrument has a three octave range going from a middle to a very high pitch.  At all pitches, the instrument has a flat timbre.  It has three registers.  The low register has a resonant timbre.  The middle register begins at mid-high pitch and has a clear dull timbre.  The high register begins at high pitch and has a reedy warm heavy timbre.

The buzat is a large stationary wooden musical instrument which uses a leather bellows to pressurize air, ultimately blowing it through any of three hundred forty-two stone pipes.  The musician directs air through chosen pipes by playing a ceramic keyboard.  The instrument has flue pipes and both single reed and free reed pipes.  The instrument has a seven octave range going from a very low to an extremely high pitch.  The instrument has a clear rich timbre.

The dîbesh is a large hand-held stone musical instrument which uses a ceramic pump to send water into a chamber, ultimately supplying air to blow through any of two hundred twenty-eight glass pipes.  The musician directs air through chosen pipes by playing a ceramic keyboard.  All of the pipes are flue pipes.  The instrument has a six octave range going from a low to an extremely high pitch.  At all pitches, the instrument has a thin focused vibrating timbre.  It has two registers.  The low register has a harsh nasal buzzy timbre.  The high register begins at mid-high pitch and has a brittle piercing strident timbre.

The rinal is a large hand-held silk-stringed instrument with a metal body.  The instrument rests flat as the musician strikes the three main strings with wooden hammers.  A drone string is occasionally struck.  Tuning is possible with adjustable bridges.  The instrument has a four octave range going from a very low to a mid-high pitch.  At all pitches, the instrument has a quavering timbre.  It has four registers.  The low register has a raucous timbre.  The middle register begins at low pitch and has a wobbling eerie timbre.  The high register begins at mid-low pitch and has a harsh nasal wispy timbre.  The top register begins at middle pitch and has a nasal muddy timbre.

The emuth is a large stationary silk-stringed instrument with a bone frame and a wooden body.  The strings are suspended from the frame down to the body and the musician picks the seventeen strings with a glass plectrum.  Tuning is accomplished by pegs.  The instrument has a four octave range going from a very low to a mid-high pitch.  At all pitches, the instrument has a fluid timbre.  It has three registers.  The low register has a noisy floating timbre.  The middle register begins at low pitch and has a reedy dark timbre.  The high register begins at middle pitch and has a graceful broad dark timbre.

The sákrith is a small hand-held silk-stringed instrument with a bone yoke and a bone body. The instrument has a nearly four octave range going from a mid-low to a very high pitch.  The instrument has a sweet timbre.

The amug is a large hand-held conical bore ceramic wind instrument.  The musician blows across a hole in the side.  The musician selects the pitch by pressing keys to stop holes. The middle register begins at low pitch and has a noisy full crisp timbre.  The high register begins at mid-low pitch and has a sparse crisp timbre.
